<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1436,838,1403]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,365,838,863]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">DIAGNOSIS:</emphasis>
This species is characterized by it lack of pronotal and abdominal pigmentation (
<figureCitation box="[1335,1423,839,863]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–95" captionStartId="63.[151,263,1985,2008]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1249,1976]" captionTargetId="figure-59@63.[151,1436,1249,2018]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 92–95. Alloperla deminuta. 92: Habitus (preserved); 93: Male terminalia; 94: Female terminalia, ventral; 95: Predicted ENM map with documented occurrences and range estimate." pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 92</figureCitation>
), whereas all other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1906" box="[357,463,875,899]" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Alloperla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[357,463,875,899]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Alloperla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[537,646,875,899]" name="Mongolia" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Mongolia</collectingCountry>
have characteristic pigmentation (
<figureCitation box="[1043,1147,875,899]" captionStart="FIGURES 100–103" captionStartId="64.[151,264,1875,1898]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1085,1812]" captionTargetId="figure-73@64.[151,1436,1085,1854]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURES 100–103. Alloperla mediata. 100: Habitus (preserved); 101: Male terminalia.; 102: Female terminalia, ventral; 103: Predicted ENM map with documented occurrences and range estimate." pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 100</figureCitation>
,). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zapekina-Dulkeit" authorityYear="1970" box="[1174,1312,875,899]" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Alloperla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="deminuta">
<emphasis box="[1174,1312,875,899]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">A. deminuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does have some faint pigmentation on the inner margin of tergite 10 forming a rectangular outline around the epiproct origin (
<figureCitation box="[159,243,947,971]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–95" captionStartId="63.[151,263,1985,2008]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1249,1976]" captionTargetId="figure-59@63.[151,1436,1249,2018]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 92–95. Alloperla deminuta. 92: Habitus (preserved); 93: Male terminalia; 94: Female terminalia, ventral; 95: Predicted ENM map with documented occurrences and range estimate." pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 93</figureCitation>
), which 
<taxonomicName authority="Zwick, 1972" authorityName="Zwick" authorityYear="1972" box="[340,583,947,971]" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Alloperla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="joosti">
<emphasis box="[340,434,947,971]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">A. joosti</emphasis>
Zwick, 1972
</taxonomicName>
lacks. Like 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zwick" authorityYear="1972" box="[722,816,947,971]" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Alloperla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="joosti">
<emphasis box="[722,816,947,971]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">A. joosti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[832,914,947,971]" captionStart="FIGURES 96–99" captionStartId="64.[151,264,983,1006]" captionTargetBox="[153,1434,193,920]" captionTargetId="figure-69@64.[151,1436,193,962]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURES 96–99. Alloperla joosti. 96: Habitus (preserved); 97: Male terminalia; 98: Female terminalia, ventral; 99: Predicted ENM map with documented occurrences and range estimate." pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 97</figureCitation>
), the base of the epiproct is narrow and not as greatly swollen (
<figureCitation box="[338,433,983,1007]" captionStart="FIGURES 108–109" captionStartId="65.[151,264,1983,2006]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1017,1974]" captionTargetId="figure-62@65.[151,1436,1017,2026]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="FIGURES 108–109. Alaskaperla and Haploperla. 108: Habitus (live), Haploperla lepnevae, Uur River (SRP2005071601); 109: Comparative distribution map." pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 109</figureCitation>
) as in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Navas" baseAuthorityYear="1925" box="[508,629,983,1007]" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Alloperla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mediata">
<emphasis box="[508,629,983,1007]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">A. mediata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[644,740,983,1007]" captionStart="FIGURES 100–103" captionStartId="64.[151,264,1875,1898]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1085,1812]" captionTargetId="figure-73@64.[151,1436,1085,1854]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURES 100–103. Alloperla mediata. 100: Habitus (preserved); 101: Male terminalia.; 102: Female terminalia, ventral; 103: Predicted ENM map with documented occurrences and range estimate." pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 101</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Klapalek" baseAuthorityYear="1923" box="[802,940,983,1007]" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Alloperla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rostellata">
<emphasis box="[802,940,983,1007]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">A. rostellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[955,1053,983,1007]" captionStart="FIGURES 104–107" captionStartId="65.[151,263,924,947]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,908]" captionTargetId="figure-58@65.[151,1436,181,950]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="FIGURES 104–107. Alloperla rostellata. 104: Habitus (preserved); 105: Male terminalia; 106: Female terminalia, ventral; 107: Predicted ENM map with documented occurrences and range estimate." pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 105</figureCitation>
). In contrast to 
<emphasis box="[1228,1328,983,1007]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zwick" authorityYear="1972" box="[1228,1324,983,1007]" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Alloperla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="joosti">A. joosti</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
the tip of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zapekina-Dulkeit" authorityYear="1970" box="[151,286,1019,1043]" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Alloperla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="deminuta">
<emphasis box="[151,286,1019,1043]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">A. deminuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’s epiproct is pointed (
<figureCitation box="[537,619,1019,1043]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–95" captionStartId="63.[151,263,1985,2008]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1249,1976]" captionTargetId="figure-59@63.[151,1436,1249,2018]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 92–95. Alloperla deminuta. 92: Habitus (preserved); 93: Male terminalia; 94: Female terminalia, ventral; 95: Predicted ENM map with documented occurrences and range estimate." pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 93</figureCitation>
) and without ventral spines. The epiproct is also shorter than in all other Mongolian 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1906" box="[286,392,1055,1079]" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Alloperla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[286,392,1055,1079]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Alloperla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The subgenitial plate of females is often difficult to discern due to lack of contrasting pigmentation (
<figureCitation box="[314,397,1091,1115]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–95" captionStartId="63.[151,263,1985,2008]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1249,1976]" captionTargetId="figure-59@63.[151,1436,1249,2018]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 92–95. Alloperla deminuta. 92: Habitus (preserved); 93: Male terminalia; 94: Female terminalia, ventral; 95: Predicted ENM map with documented occurrences and range estimate." pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 94</figureCitation>
). The plate is flat with a small subtriangular protrusion in the middle that barely extends over sternum 8. In other species, this plate is more pointed and much longer, usually covering more of sternum 9. Nymphs are readily distinguishable at the generic level, but comparative material was insufficient to define characters for separating species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
