<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1436,838,1403]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,379,1306,1331]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">DISCUSSION:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zapekina-Dulkeit" authorityYear="1970" box="[388,525,1307,1331]" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Alloperla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="deminuta">
<emphasis box="[388,525,1307,1331]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">A. deminuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the most commonly encountered 
<taxonomicName box="[941,1137,1307,1331]" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Alloperla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[941,1047,1307,1331]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Alloperla</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[1177,1286,1307,1331]" name="Mongolia" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Mongolia</collectingCountry>
and is found predominantly in the 
<collectingRegion box="[389,477,1343,1367]" country="Mongolia" name="Selenge" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Selenge</collectingRegion>
River Basin (
<figureCitation box="[631,714,1343,1367]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–95" captionStartId="63.[151,263,1985,2008]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1249,1976]" captionTargetId="figure-59@63.[151,1436,1249,2018]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 92–95. Alloperla deminuta. 92: Habitus (preserved); 93: Male terminalia; 94: Female terminalia, ventral; 95: Predicted ENM map with documented occurrences and range estimate." pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 95</figureCitation>
). This species is unique among Mongolian 
<taxonomicName box="[1196,1364,1343,1367]" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Chloroperlidae</taxonomicName>
for its extreme lack of dark pigmentation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
